statement:
Suppose the motion of a spring-mass system is described by the following
differential equation

\begin{align*}2u'' + 2\gamma u' + 18u = 0, \quad u(0) = 1, u'(0) = -\frac{11}2\end{align*}

\textbf{(b)} Solve the following equation for \emph{u}(\emph{t}) in
explicit form.

\begin{align*}u'' + 6u' + 25u = 15\cos(5t), \quad u(0) = 1, u'(0) = -\frac{11}2\end{align*}

sols:
Notice that the ODE

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}u'' + 6u' + 25u = 15 \cos(5t)\end{align*}

has a nonzero right-hand side. We will begin by solving the homogeneous
equation

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}u'' + 6u' + 25u = 0.\end{align*}

By making the ansatz $u = \exp(rt)$ we arrive at

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}r^2 + 6r + 25 = 0\end{align*}

with roots $r = -3 \pm 4 i$. Complex roots of the form $a+ib$ lead to
solutions of the form

\begin{align*}
&e^{at}\sin(bt)\\
&e^{at}\cos(bt).\end{align*}

Therefore the homogeneous solution is

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}u_h = C_1 e^{-3t} \sin(4t) + C_2 e^{-3t} \cos(4t).\end{align*}

The right-hand side is sinusoidal with argument $5t$. We need to think
of which functions (and their derivatives) that could lead to this
possible right-hand side. The only such possible functions are

\begin{align*}
\cos(5t)\\
\sin(5t)\end{align*}

and so, we will find a particular solution of the form

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}u_p = A \sin(5t) + B \cos(5t).\end{align*}

Taking this particular solution and plugging it in to the ODE, we have:

\begin{align*}
(-25 A \sin(5t) - 25 B \cos(5t)) + 6(5 A \cos(5t) - 5B \sin(5t)) + 25(A \sin(5t) + B \cos(5t)) &= 15 \cos(5t)
\\ -30B \sin(5t) + 30A \cos(5t) &= 15 \cos(5t)\end{align*}

In comparing the coefficients of $\sin(5t)$ and $\cos(5t)$, we find that

\begin{align*}
B &= 0\\
A &= 1/2.\end{align*}

The general solution to the ODE will be $u = u_h + u_p$, giving

\begin{align*}u = \frac{1}{2} \sin(5t) + C_1 e^{-3t} \sin(4t) + C_2 e^{-3t} \cos(4t).\end{align*}

The initial conditions tell us

\begin{align*}
u(0)&=1\\
u'(0)&=-\frac{11}{2}\end{align*}

From this, we have,

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}u(0) = C_2 = 1\end{align*}

and

\begin{align*}u'(0) = \left.\left(\frac{5}{2} \cos(5t) - 3 C_1 e^{-3t} \sin(4t) + 4 C_1 e^{-3t} \cos(4t) - 3 C_2 e^{-3t} \cos(4t) - 4 C_2 e^{-3t} \sin(4t)\right)\right|_{t=0} = \frac{5}{2} + 4 C_1 - 3 = \frac{-11}{2}.\end{align*}

Therefore we get that

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}C_1 = -5/4.\end{align*}

The solution is thus

\begin{align*}u(t) = \frac{1}{2} \sin(5t) - \frac{5}{4} e^{-3t} \sin(4t) + e^{-3t} \cos(4t).\end{align*}
